Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Remove the
@Puff Pastry Sheet{1%pack} from your fridge and allow to come up to
room temperature.

Chop the @Potatoes{450%grams} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel).

Pop them onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @Olive Oil{2%tbsp}, sprinkle
over the @Dried Rosemary{1%sachet}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss
to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden,
~{25-35%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} on high heat. Pat
the @Salmon Fillets{2} dry with #kitchen paper{}, then season with salt and
pepper.

Once hot, carefully place the salmon into the #pan{}, skin-side down. Fry
for ~{1%minute}, then turn over and cook for ~{30%seconds} on the other side -
the salmon will be sealed but not cooked through (it'll finish cooking in
the oven).

Transfer to a #plate{} and allow to cool.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw fish.

Meanwhile, in a large #bowl{}, combine the @Cider Vinegar{15%ml}, a drizzle of
olive oil and the @Sugar{1/2%tsp}. Season with salt and pepper, then set aside.

Quarter the @Pear{1/2} lengthways (no need to peel), remove the core and thinly
slice lengthways.

In a small bowl, combine the @Fig Jam{40%g} and olive oil. Crumble in the
@Goat's Cheese{75%g}, then mix until smooth.

Keeping the puff pastry on the paper it comes on, cut it into quarters to make
2 rectangles per person.

Once the salmon has cooled slightly, peel off and discard the skin. Sprinkle
over the @Lemon & Herb Seasoning{1%sachet}.

Place a salmon fillet in the middle of a rectangle of pastry, leaving a border
all around it. Coat the fish with some of the fig jam and goat's cheese
filling.

Lay another rectangle of pastry on top, pressing it down on all sides so the
salmon sits snugly inside. Trim the edges to neaten them and seal shut with
the back of a #fork{}.

Repeat with the remaining salmon, filling and pastry.

> TIP: Brush the top of the pastry with a little milk if you have some.

Transfer the paper with your salmon en croute parcels to a baking tray.

Bake on the middle shelf of your oven until the pastry is golden brown and the
fish is cooked through, ~{15-20%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The fish is cooked when opaque in the middle.

When everything's ready, add the sliced pear and @Baby Leaf Mix{20%g} to the
bowl of dressing. Toss to coat.

Share the salmon en croutes between your plates.

Serve the rosemary roast potatoes and pear salad alongside. Add a dollop of
@Mayonnaise{1%tbsp} alongside for dipping.

Enjoy!